    slug: "talaq-kay-masail",
    description: `Talaq Kay Masail is an Urdu-language Islamic book that provides a detailed and scholarly treatment of the legal rulings and practical issues related to divorce (talaq) in Islamic law. Written in clear, accessible Urdu, the book addresses one of the most sensitive and consequential areas of Islamic family law with the gravity, thoroughness, and compassion that the topic demands. Divorce is recognized in Islam as a permissible but deeply disliked act, described by the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) as the most hated of all permissible things in the sight of Allah. The book approaches this subject with the understanding that while divorce should always be a last resort, Muslims need clear, accurate, and comprehensive guidance on how Islamic law governs the process when it becomes necessary.

The book covers the complete framework of talaq as understood in Islamic jurisprudence, beginning with the different types of divorce recognized in Sharia — talaq al-sunnah (the prophetic method, which is revocable and follows the prescribed procedure) and talaq al-bidah (the innovated method, which involves issuing three divorces simultaneously and is considered sinful though legally effective according to the majority of scholars). For each type, the author explains the precise legal conditions, the method of pronouncement, the waiting period (iddah), the financial obligations of the husband during and after the iddah, and the revocability or irreversibility of the divorce. The book also covers khula (the wife's right to initiate dissolution of the marriage), faskh (annulment by a judicial authority), and the grounds on which each of these procedures may be pursued.

A significant and highly practical section of the book addresses contemporary issues related to divorce that are frequently encountered in Muslim communities but often poorly understood. These include the validity of divorce pronounced under duress, in a state of anger, or while intoxicated; the effect of written or text-message divorces in the modern context; the three-talaq-in-one-sitting issue and the ongoing scholarly debate about its legal status; the question of conditional divorce (talaq muallaq) and whether conditional statements constitute an actual divorce; and the procedures for reconciliation (ruju) during the iddah period. The author presents the positions of the major schools of Islamic jurisprudence on each issue, citing the relevant Quranic verses, hadith narrations, and scholarly opinions, and noting where legitimate differences of opinion exist. Talaq Kay Masail is an essential reference for Islamic scholars, qadis (judges), counselors, and any Muslim seeking reliable guidance on this critical area of personal and family law.`,
    metaDescription: "Talaq Kay Masail is a comprehensive Urdu Islamic book covering divorce laws, types of talaq, khula, and contemporary marital issues in Sharia."
